---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="Deck Resurfacing | New Boards, or Boards + Railings | Belvedere Decks"
  description="Deck resurfacing in Maryland: new composite deck boards on your existing frame (starting at $8k), or boards plus new railings for a complete transformation (starting at $13k). Honest frame inspection first."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Deck Resurfacing · Starting at $8,000</p>
      <h1>Your deck's bones are good. Everything you touch is worn out.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
      <p class="lead">
        Most Maryland decks built between 1985 and 2010 sit on a frame with decades of
        life left, under boards and railings that are done. Resurfacing replaces what
        you see and touch, and keeps the good structure you already paid for.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Two ways to do it: pick your level</h2>
      <table class="compare">
        <thead>
          <tr><th style="width:22%"></th><th>New Boards Only</th><th>Boards + New Railings</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th>What changes</th>
            <td data-label="New Boards Only">Every deck board replaced with premium composite, fastened with hidden screws, with nothing to catch a bare foot. Your existing railings stay.</td>
            <td data-label="Boards + New Railings">Everything you can see and touch is new: boards, railings, posts, and the trim that wraps the deck's edge. From the yard, it reads as a brand-new deck.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Best when</th>
            <td data-label="New Boards Only">Your railings are solid and you still like them.</td>
            <td data-label="Boards + New Railings">Railings are wobbly, dated, or you want the complete transformation.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Starting price</th>
            <td data-label="New Boards Only"><strong>Starting at $8,000</strong> (160–400 sq ft)</td>
            <td data-label="Boards + New Railings"><strong>Starting at $13,000</strong> (160–400 sq ft)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Typical time</th>
            <td data-label="New Boards Only">A few days</td>
            <td data-label="Boards + New Railings">A few days to a week</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Photos</th>
            <td data-label="New Boards Only"><!-- TODO: before/after pair - boards-only project -->Before &amp; after photos coming as projects complete.</td>
            <td data-label="Boards + New Railings"><!-- TODO: before/after pair - full transformation -->Before &amp; after photos coming as projects complete.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Not sure which your deck needs? That's what the free visit is for. We'll tell you plainly, even when the answer is the smaller number.</p>

      <!-- Manufacturer imagery is OK on this page (never on Our Work). -->
      <figure class="site-figure" style="margin: 2rem 0;">
        <img src="/images/timbertech/edge-coconut-husk-picture-frame-2.jpg"
          alt="TimberTech composite deck in Coconut Husk with a Sea Salt Gray picture-frame border" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>
          The bordered "picture frame" edge we build standard — shown here in TimberTech
          Coconut Husk with a Sea Salt Gray border. <a href="/decking">See all boards &amp; colors</a>.
          <span class="photo-credit">Photo courtesy of TimberTech — shown for product reference.</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h2>Every resurfacing project starts the same way</h2>
      <p>
        An honest look at the frame underneath. We test the posts, check where the deck
        attaches to your house, and measure the spacing of the support boards (the
        joists). Composite decking needs them 16 inches apart or closer. If your
        structure isn't sound, we tell you before you spend a dollar on boards.
      </p>

      <h2>What's always included</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Careful removal of the old boards (and railings, on the full transformation)</li>
        <li>Full inspection of the frame underneath, narrated out loud as we go</li>
        <li>Replacement of any rotted or bowed support boards. An allowance is written into your contract, so there's never a surprise charge</li>
        <li>Waterproof tape on top of the frame, the detail that doubles its life under composite</li>
        <li>Premium TimberTech or Trex boards with hidden fasteners</li>
        <li>Railings checked to safety standards: 36 inches tall, pickets no more than 4 inches apart</li>
        <li>Haul-away of everything old</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="notice">
        Resurfacing typically needs no building permit, because the frame stays in
        place. If we find structural work is needed, we confirm the county's
        requirements first and put it in writing before anything changes.
      </div>

      <p><a class="btn primary" href="/estimate">Get a Free Estimate</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
